1
00:00:00,089 --> 00:00:05,990
In today’s video I’ll show you my secret
process to find the BEST stocks to day trade,

2
00:00:05,990 --> 00:00:11,420
and the system I have in place to filter out
the bad stocks and focus on the ones with

3
00:00:11,420 --> 00:00:13,750
the highest profit potential.

4
00:00:13,750 --> 00:00:17,590
First, you want to look for stocks that are
liquid.

5
00:00:17,590 --> 00:00:22,109
This means that there are a lot of buyers
and sellers in the market, which makes it

6
00:00:22,109 --> 00:00:27,220
easier to enter and exit trades without affecting
the price too much.

7
00:00:27,220 --> 00:00:30,640
Also, you want to focus on stocks that are
volatile.

8
00:00:30,640 --> 00:00:36,309
A stock that moves a lot in price throughout
the day gives you more chances to buy low

9
00:00:36,309 --> 00:00:37,880
and sell high.

10
00:00:37,880 --> 00:00:42,210
Another important factor to consider is the
overall market trend.

11
00:00:42,210 --> 00:00:47,219
You want to trade stocks that are moving in
the same direction as the overall market.

12
00:00:47,219 --> 00:00:52,350
So when the market is bullish, you want to
trade stocks that are showing strength.

13
00:00:52,350 --> 00:00:53,750
Now let’s get specific.

14
00:00:53,750 --> 00:00:58,239
Here are the exact filters that I always use
in Finviz screener.

15
00:00:58,239 --> 00:00:59,370
1.

16
00:00:59,370 --> 00:01:04,110
Average Volume
Average Volume is perhaps the most important

17
00:01:04,110 --> 00:01:07,430
filter for finding liquid stocks.

18
00:01:07,430 --> 00:01:12,360
Average volume refers to the number of shares
traded on average each day.

19
00:01:12,360 --> 00:01:16,350
The higher the volume, the more liquid the
stock is likely to be.

20
00:01:16,350 --> 00:01:22,790
I usually set this filter to "Over 1 million
shares" to ensure that there are enough buyers

21
00:01:22,790 --> 00:01:24,850
and sellers in the market.

22
00:01:24,850 --> 00:01:31,400
The more shares that are being traded each
day, the easier it is to enter and exit positions

23
00:01:31,400 --> 00:01:33,751
without causing a major impact on the price.

24
00:01:33,751 --> 00:01:34,751
2.

25
00:01:34,751 --> 00:01:40,810
Price
While not directly related to liquidity, the

26
00:01:40,810 --> 00:01:45,020
price of a stock can also impact how easily
you can trade it.

27
00:01:45,020 --> 00:01:51,030
I generally recommend setting the price filter
to "Over $30 dollars", to avoid stocks that

28
00:01:51,030 --> 00:01:54,719
are too cheap and may not have enough volume.

29
00:01:54,719 --> 00:01:59,960
Setting the price filter to "Over 30 dollars"
can be a good way to ensure that you're trading

30
00:01:59,960 --> 00:02:02,969
stocks with adequate liquidity.

31
00:02:02,969 --> 00:02:08,090
These stocks tend to attract more institutional
investors and large traders.

32
00:02:08,090 --> 00:02:14,140
I try to avoid lower-priced stocks because
they often have smaller market capitalizations

33
00:02:14,140 --> 00:02:19,910
and fewer shares outstanding, which can make
them more susceptible to big price swings

34
00:02:19,910 --> 00:02:21,290
and manipulation.

35
00:02:21,290 --> 00:02:22,400
3.

36
00:02:22,400 --> 00:02:24,629
Relative volume

37
00:02:24,629 --> 00:02:29,110
Another important filter you must use is the
relative volume.

38
00:02:29,110 --> 00:02:34,810
Relative Volume compares the current trading
volume of a stock to its average volume over

39
00:02:34,810 --> 00:02:39,200
a specific period, typically the past 30 trading
days.

40
00:02:39,200 --> 00:02:44,710
When a stock is trading at a higher volume
than usual, it tells us that there's increased

41
00:02:44,710 --> 00:02:48,040
interest and activity around that stock.

42
00:02:48,040 --> 00:02:53,319
And when there's increased interest in a stock,
there's often a greater potential for significant

43
00:02:53,319 --> 00:02:54,730
price action.

44
00:02:54,730 --> 00:03:00,310
I recommend setting the Relative Volume filter
to Over 1, when looking for stocks to day

45
00:03:00,310 --> 00:03:01,660
trade or scalp.

46
00:03:01,660 --> 00:03:07,390
A Relative Volume of 1 means that the stock
is trading at its average volume.

47
00:03:07,390 --> 00:03:13,100
Also, if you want to be more aggressive, you
could set the Relative Volume filter to Over

48
00:03:13,100 --> 00:03:14,100
2.

49
00:03:14,100 --> 00:03:20,220
A Relative Volume above 2 indicates that the
stock is trading at more than twice its normal

50
00:03:20,220 --> 00:03:26,110
volume, which is a strong signal of increased
market interest and potential for significant

51
00:03:26,110 --> 00:03:27,989
price action.

52
00:03:27,989 --> 00:03:29,409
4.

53
00:03:29,409 --> 00:03:33,939
Beta
As short-term traders, we're looking for stocks

54
00:03:33,939 --> 00:03:37,450
that can make big moves in a short period
of time.

55
00:03:37,450 --> 00:03:42,340
We want to get in, ride the momentum, and
get out with a quick profit.

56
00:03:42,340 --> 00:03:47,460
And stocks with a high beta are more likely
to give us those opportunities.

57
00:03:47,460 --> 00:03:52,930
Beta is a measure of a stock's volatility
in relation to the overall market, as represented

58
00:03:52,930 --> 00:03:55,560
by the S&P 500 index.

59
00:03:55,560 --> 00:04:00,690
Essentially, it quantifies how sensitive a
stock is to broad market swings.

60
00:04:00,690 --> 00:04:03,890
Now, the market beta baseline is 1.

61
00:04:03,890 --> 00:04:10,510
So stocks with a beta above 1 tend to be more
volatile than the general market, while stocks

62
00:04:10,510 --> 00:04:14,780
with a beta below 1 tend to be less volatile.

63
00:04:14,780 --> 00:04:20,310
By screening specifically for stocks with
a beta higher than 1, we focus on names that

64
00:04:20,310 --> 00:04:25,970
historically demonstrate above average volatility
compared to the market.

65
00:04:25,970 --> 00:04:32,789
A beta of 1.5, for example, means that the
stock is 50% more volatile than the market.

66
00:04:32,789 --> 00:04:39,890
So, if the market moves up 1%, the stock should
theoretically move up 1.5%.

67
00:04:39,890 --> 00:04:44,979
By setting the beta filter to Over 1, you
can quickly narrow down your list of potential

68
00:04:44,979 --> 00:04:48,560
trades to only the most volatile names.

69
00:04:48,560 --> 00:04:55,180
Depending on market conditions and your strategy,
you might set the filter to Over 1.5 or even

70
00:04:55,180 --> 00:04:56,699
Over 2.

71
00:04:56,699 --> 00:04:57,699
5.

72
00:04:57,699 --> 00:05:02,690
Market cap
I also set the market cap filter to Over 1

73
00:05:02,690 --> 00:05:04,199
billion dollars.

74
00:05:04,199 --> 00:05:10,840
This way, we can quickly narrow down our list
of potential trades to only the most established

75
00:05:10,840 --> 00:05:13,180
and actively traded names.

76
00:05:13,180 --> 00:05:18,259
When we're talking about stocks with a market
cap over 1 billion dollars, we're talking

77
00:05:18,259 --> 00:05:20,030
about the big leagues.

78
00:05:20,030 --> 00:05:25,220
These are the companies that have the attention
of the major players on Wall Street.

79
00:05:25,220 --> 00:05:31,340
Stocks with a market cap over 1 billion dollars
also tend to be more stable and less prone

80
00:05:31,340 --> 00:05:32,940
to manipulation.

81
00:05:32,940 --> 00:05:38,480
These are established companies with solid
fundamentals and a track record of success.

82
00:05:38,480 --> 00:05:39,480
6.

83
00:05:39,480 --> 00:05:44,530
Average True Range
The Average True Range is one of my favorite

84
00:05:44,530 --> 00:05:49,310
indicators for measuring volatility and potential
profit opportunities.

85
00:05:49,310 --> 00:05:55,819
In simple terms, ATR measures the average
range of a stock's price movement over a given

86
00:05:55,819 --> 00:05:59,090
period of time, typically 14 days.

87
00:05:59,090 --> 00:06:04,660
When a stock has a high ATR, it means that
it's experiencing significant price swings

88
00:06:04,660 --> 00:06:06,389
on a regular basis.

89
00:06:06,389 --> 00:06:12,280
The price is moving up and down more dramatically
than a stock with a lower ATR.

90
00:06:12,280 --> 00:06:16,600
I like to set the w filter on Finviz to "Over
1".

91
00:06:16,600 --> 00:06:21,910
This helps me quickly identify stocks that
are experiencing a high level of volatility,

92
00:06:21,910 --> 00:06:25,030
and potential for significant price movement.

93
00:06:25,030 --> 00:06:30,470
And that's exactly what we want to see as
day traders - stocks that are making big moves

94
00:06:30,470 --> 00:06:32,720
and creating opportunities.

95
00:06:32,720 --> 00:06:34,300
7.

96
00:06:34,300 --> 00:06:38,420
Float
The size of a stock's float can also have

97
00:06:38,420 --> 00:06:42,220
a big impact on its volatility and liquidity.

98
00:06:42,220 --> 00:06:46,819
When we talk about a stock's float, we're
talking about the number of shares that are

99
00:06:46,819 --> 00:06:50,840
actually available for trading on the open
market.

100
00:06:50,840 --> 00:06:56,100
That's why I usually recommend setting the
float filter to Over 10 million when scanning

101
00:06:56,100 --> 00:06:58,070
for potential trades.

102
00:06:58,070 --> 00:07:02,849
This helps to ensure that there are enough
shares available for trading, and that the

103
00:07:02,849 --> 00:07:07,840
stock is less likely to experience sudden,
erratic price swings.

104
00:07:07,840 --> 00:07:09,040
8.

105
00:07:09,040 --> 00:07:11,440
50 SMA

106
00:07:11,440 --> 00:07:17,060
The 50-Day Simple moving average is my go-to
indicator to get a more complete picture of

107
00:07:17,060 --> 00:07:18,379
a stock's trend.

108
00:07:18,379 --> 00:07:23,389
You can also use the 20-Day moving average,
as an additional filter.

109
00:07:23,389 --> 00:07:29,980
The 20-Day SMA is a shorter-term indicator
that's more sensitive to recent price action.

110
00:07:29,980 --> 00:07:35,110
It's great for identifying potential trend
changes in the near term.

111
00:07:35,110 --> 00:07:40,599
The 50-Day SMA is a longer-term indicator
that's less sensitive to short-term price

112
00:07:40,599 --> 00:07:41,970
fluctuations.

113
00:07:41,970 --> 00:07:47,780
It takes more time to change course, but when
it does, it can be a powerful signal of a

114
00:07:47,780 --> 00:07:50,250
more significant trend change.

115
00:07:50,250 --> 00:07:56,400
If a stock is trading above both the 20-Day
and 50-Day SMA, that's a strong sign that

116
00:07:56,400 --> 00:07:58,949
it's in a well-established uptrend.

117
00:07:58,949 --> 00:08:04,169
The shorter-term and longer-term trends are
aligned, and the stock has a lot of bullish

118
00:08:04,169 --> 00:08:07,450
momentum behind it.

119
00:08:07,450 --> 00:08:09,690
9.

120
00:08:09,690 --> 00:08:10,690
Gap up

121
00:08:10,690 --> 00:08:15,430
An up gap occurs when a stock opens significantly
higher than its previous day's close.

122
00:08:15,430 --> 00:08:20,940
Gaps are often a sign of strong momentum and
sentiment in a particular direction.

123
00:08:20,940 --> 00:08:25,870
When a stock gaps up, it means that there
was a lot of buying pressure and demand for

124
00:08:25,870 --> 00:08:30,840
that stock in the pre-market or after-hours
trading sessions.

125
00:08:30,840 --> 00:08:36,550
This is why I love to use the Gap Up Over
1% filter, when I'm scanning for potential

126
00:08:36,550 --> 00:08:38,260
momentum trades.

127
00:08:38,260 --> 00:08:44,709
By looking for stocks that have gapped up
by more than 1%, I can quickly identify names

128
00:08:44,709 --> 00:08:50,610
that are experiencing significant overnight
moves and that may be poised for continued

129
00:08:50,610 --> 00:08:52,899
momentum in the same direction.

130
00:08:52,899 --> 00:08:59,769
For example, if a stock gaps up on high volume
and with a wide range, that's often a sign

131
00:08:59,769 --> 00:09:05,130
of strong bullish momentum that could continue
throughout the trading day.

132
00:09:05,130 --> 00:09:10,399
Combined with the previous filter, the 50-day
moving average, if the broader market is in

133
00:09:10,399 --> 00:09:16,459
an uptrend and experiencing positive sentiment,
that may provide a tailwind for stocks that

134
00:09:16,459 --> 00:09:20,440
gap up, and increase the likelihood of continued
momentum.

135
00:09:20,440 --> 00:09:21,620
10.

136
00:09:21,620 --> 00:09:23,980
52-Week High/Low

137
00:09:23,980 --> 00:09:29,579
The 52-Week High-Low filter is a powerful
tool for identifying stocks that are trading

138
00:09:29,579 --> 00:09:35,790
near their highest levels in the past year,
and that may be poised for a breakout or continuation

139
00:09:35,790 --> 00:09:36,930
move.

140
00:09:36,930 --> 00:09:42,690
These are the highest and lowest prices that
a stock has traded at over the past year,

141
00:09:42,690 --> 00:09:44,490
or 52 weeks.

142
00:09:44,490 --> 00:09:50,010
They represent the extremes of a stock's price
range during that time period, and can provide

143
00:09:50,010 --> 00:09:53,640
important context for its current price action.

144
00:09:53,640 --> 00:09:59,700
I like to use the “0% - 10% below high”
filter, and we're looking for stocks that

145
00:09:59,700 --> 00:10:04,560
are trading within 10% of their 52-week high
price.

146
00:10:04,560 --> 00:10:10,160
In other words, we want to find stocks that
are close to breaking out to new highs, but

147
00:10:10,160 --> 00:10:12,589
haven't quite gotten there yet.

148
00:10:12,589 --> 00:10:18,760
When a stock is trading near its 52-week high,
it means that there is a lot of bullish sentiment

149
00:10:18,760 --> 00:10:20,900
and momentum behind it.

150
00:10:20,900 --> 00:10:26,610
And by focusing on stocks that are very close
to making new highs, you will easily identify

151
00:10:26,610 --> 00:10:31,150
names that may be on the verge of a big move
higher.

152
00:10:31,150 --> 00:10:37,470
By combining these 10 filters, you're essentially
creating a powerful system that identifies

153
00:10:37,470 --> 00:10:40,760
the most promising stocks for day trading.

154
00:10:40,760 --> 00:10:46,490
Remember - the market is always changing,
and you’ll need to be flexible in your approach.

155
00:10:46,490 --> 00:10:51,220
There may be times when applying all these
filters will result in a very small list of

156
00:10:51,220 --> 00:10:53,480
stocks, or even no stocks at all.

157
00:10:53,480 --> 00:11:00,340
In these situations, it's okay to adjust slightly
the strategy and loosen some of the filters,

158
00:11:00,340 --> 00:11:03,089
to widen your pool of potential trades.

159
00:11:03,089 --> 00:11:09,120
For example, if you're left with only several
stocks to choose from, skip the “gap up”

160
00:11:09,120 --> 00:11:12,930
filter or adjust the “52-Week High Low”
one.

161
00:11:12,930 --> 00:11:18,190
This will expand your list to include more
potential stocks to day trade.

162
00:11:18,190 --> 00:11:23,260
By using this comprehensive set of filters,
you're putting the odds in your favor and

163
00:11:23,260 --> 00:11:29,880
giving yourself the best possible chance to
find the stocks with the highest profit potential.

164
00:11:29,880 --> 00:11:32,350
And now it’s time to trade them.

165
00:11:32,350 --> 00:11:36,069
These videos will show you my favorite day-trading
strategies.

